{"runId":"openai-gpt-oss-120b-nitro@2026-05-13T16-43-10-595Z","slug":"the-unassuming-power-of-multiple-choice-questions","locale":"hi","model":"openai/gpt-oss-120b:nitro","modelPath":"openai-gpt-oss-120b-nitro","createdAt":"2026-05-13T16:43:16.180Z","sourcePath":"src/content/posts/2025-01-01--the-unassuming-power-of-multiple-choice-questions/index.mdx","targetPath":"src/content/posts/2025-01-01--the-unassuming-power-of-multiple-choice-questions/hi/index.mdx","candidatePath":"reports/i18n/the-unassuming-power-of-multiple-choice-questions/hi/openai-gpt-oss-120b-nitro/2026-05-13T16-43-10-595Z/candidate.mdx","sourceHash":"caa10164f80350a5733ad5c3d7edf12b50afa0765cd3d9f8fd3c5758259550be","outputHash":"675c0355bfd833895eb019fdef7c7f9ca550e1c28b5e2e7ff520bfff8f60f84b","reasoningEffort":"low","temperature":0.3,"maxTokens":16000,"timeoutMs":200000,"articleSummary":"The article argues that well‑designed multiple‑choice questions (MCQs) are a powerful teaching tool, not merely a cheap assessment method. By crafting distractors that embody common misconceptions—such as legacy syntax, cross‑platform habits, or edge‑case misunderstandings—each wrong answer reveals the learner’s mental model and delivers instructional value before any explanation is given. The author illustrates this with a PostgreSQL identity‑column quiz that simultaneously serves beginners, intermediates, and experts, showing how a single question can surface multiple layers of knowledge. The piece is aimed at educators, technical writers, and content creators who build programming quizzes, and its tone is an analytical tutorial that uses the metaphor of “the distractor as the curriculum” to frame its points.","totalInputTokens":5858,"totalOutputTokens":1458,"totalCacheReadTokens":2816,"totalCacheWriteTokens":0,"totalDurationMs":2778,"totalCostUsd":0.000490902,"pricingSource":"local-openrouter-estimate","telemetry":{"model":"openai/gpt-oss-120b:nitro","chunkSize":"6p","totalChunks":6,"totalInputTokens":5858,"tot